body:
I'm somehow a fulltime CoffeeScript programmer.
Here's what I found in 0.13 beta release post:
http://facebook.github.io/react/blog/2015/01/27/react-v0.13.0-beta-1.html

``` coffee
div = React.createFactory 'div'

class Counter extends React.Component
  @propTypes = initialCount: React.PropTypes.number
  @defaultProps = initialCount: 0

  constructor: (props) ->
    super props
    @state = count: props.initialCount

  tick: =>
    @setState count: @state.count + 1

  render: ->
    div onClick: @tick,
      'Clicks: '
      @state.count
```

While it's exciting I got some questions on using static properties:

`propTypes` and `defaultProps` are becoming static properties, and `state` is now a property defined in the constructor. And this is even more clear in the ES6 demo.

``` js
export class Counter extends React.Component {
  constructor(props) {
    super(props);
    this.state = {count: props.initialCount};
  }
  tick() {
    this.setState({count: this.state.count + 1});
  }
  render() {
    return (
      <div onClick={this.tick.bind(this)}>
        Clicks: {this.state.count}
      </div>
    );
  }
}
Counter.propTypes = { initialCount: React.PropTypes.number };
Counter.defaultProps = { initialCount: 0 };
```

I found these are not updated in the 0.13 docs, but would like to talk more about them. Which properties are influenced? Which syntax do you recommend? Fat arrow or not?
